status_message: We greet our first-year Hawkeyes tomorrow. Here's what to know about this year's move-in process: http://spr.ly/6182B2Rzi

First-year Hawkeyes, for the past few years you've tolerated your parents' slow pace. You walked on ahead, texting and tweeting as they ambled along. You tolerated their endless questions, rolled your eyes when they asked you about school, about relationships, or about that best friend you had in sixth grade. And you put up with their curfews‚Äîof course pushing the boundaries when you could. Today, we salute you as you celebrate your new home and your hard-earned independence! But as you celebrate, take a moment to remember that you and your parents once walked hand in hand. You asked endless questions of your own, and you basked in their attention. So while you're unpacking, remember who helped you get here‚Äîand say thank you. They will miss you more than you know.

When Archibald (Archie) Alexander wasn't welding iron, he was recording tackles on the gridiron. As the second black Hawkeye football player and the first black graduate of the UI College of Engineering in 1912, Alexander broke through two deeply entrenched barriers. 
 
His civil engineering degree prepared him to establish his engineering firm and specialize in constructing bridges, power plants, and freeways. His firm gained a national reputation, based on numerous projects done in Washington, D.C.
 
Photo from the Nov. 18, 1911, Iowa-Iowa State football program, UI Libraries.

On Friday, Feb. 12, 1875 ‚Äì 141 years ago ‚Äì a bright orange streak in the sky, a rumble like thunder, and shaking ground was experienced by residents in Amana, Iowa. A meteor had broken apart between the towns of South Amana and Homestead, and was referred to as the Amana Meteorite. UI professor Gustavus Hinrichs and railroad surveyor Charles Wood Irish were among those who collected meteorite samples and wrote about the event.  

Map from "An Account of the Detonating Meteor," by Charles Wood Irish, 1877. Additional writings on the the Amana Meteorite are available at University of Iowa Libraries.

#tbt In 1959, 4-year-old Amy (Ray) Kanellis fell in love with Herky. Traveling with her parents in the official UI Rose Bowl party, Amy had access to the parade float warehouse. That's where she saw him: Herky atop the UI entry. A Rose Bowl staff member asked Amy if she wanted a souvenir. She pointed to Herky: "I want him."  
 
Months later, a delivery truck pulled up to the Ray home in Iowa City and dropped off an enormous wooden crate. Inside was Herky.  

Over the years, Amy and husband Mike Kanellis gave Herky a home. When their son, Alex, played for Iowa, Herky "tailgated" in the living room.

Today, in celebration of the Hawkeye's sixth Rose Bowl appearance, the Kanellis's have put 1959 Herky is on display at the College of Dentistry and Dental Clinics, University of Iowa, where Mike is dean for patient care. Come mingle with Hawkeye history!

The UI's Operator Performance Laboratory (OPL) is working with Rockwell Collins to advance the technology for unmanned aircraft systems, more commonly known as drones.

"The next two to three years are going to be very exciting," says Alex Postnikov, a researcher in the Advanced Technology Center at Rockwell Collins.

Developing technology for a drone to behave autonomously should it lose radio contact with its operator will be key for the aircraft's commercial expansion.

Tom Schnell, director of OPL, says drones could revolutionize the areas of river and flood management, precision agriculture, large livestock operations and ranching, the railroad industry, and possibly even firefighting and law enforcement.

Why did Hawkeye Football freshman Parker Hesse choose the UI?

"Obviously there's a great tradition here at the university, a lot of great programs. That's a reason a lot of the guys come here. We have guys who obviously fit from the football program standpoint, but they also feel that they have a good opportunity for life after football with the academics here."

We're proud of our student-athletes for being winners on and off the field. Learn about senior Cole Fisher's choice to major in engineering: 

"It was actually a class I took back in seventh grade. They called it industrial technology. I had a module in it called towers. I made a little tower out of balsa wood, which I enjoyed a lot and that's what kind of got me interested in engineering ever since then." 

For more on engineering at the UI, visit: http://spr.ly/6180BT8HI.

It's no surprise Hannah Shirey is a student in The University of Iowa College of Law. Her family includes seven graduates of the UI ‚Äì four from the College of Law in particular ‚Äì spanning nearly 140 years.

Even though having a family full of Hawkeyes helped spark Shirey's interest in Iowa Law, she says her decision was solidified when she visited campus and learned more about the school's academic culture.

"What stood out to me was the student body being very well-rounded. The law school is full of very smart and engaged people, but people who are also very humble and cooperative. I wanted to work really hard and be around people who are passionate," Shirey says.
link_name: Following family precedent at Iowa Law

#TBT When the University Team played its first intercollegiate football game in October 1889, this booklet of rules was published by a local Rules Committee. It includes seven definitions, thirteen rules and eleven advertisements. Rule number 12-d reads: "It shall be a foul to throw or hand the ball in any way." A forward pass was eventually allowed in college football in 1906.

#TBT Many Hawkeye fans know that All-American Nile Kinnick died during his World War II service. Fewer are probably aware of the UI's first, first-team All-American, Fred H. Becker, who played center and right tackle in 1916. He was known for opening holes in defensive lines. Shown here, he is throwing the block for the ball carrier in a game against Nebraska. His life was cut short when he died in action during World War I's Battle of Chateau-Thierry on July 18, 1918. Becker was inducted into the University of Iowa Athletics Hall of Fame in 2009.

#TBT UI Army ROTC cadets arrived at the Pentacrest as part of the 2014 Army ROTC Game Ball Run, an event to deliver the Cy-Hawk football series game ball. The tradition helps celebrate a storied rivalry and thank Iowa veterans and troops currently deployed for their service to our nation. 

The 28th annual Army ROTC Game Ball Run is set to begin Friday morning. UI cadets will run the ball from Kinnick Stadium and make stops in Williamsburg, Marengo, and Belle Plaine before handing it off to ISU's Army ROTC in Tama. #TBT Julian Bond, who died this past weekend at age 75, was a civil rights leader who co-founded the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee in 1960. As a national advocate and Georgia state legislator, he visited UI at least twice, in April 1974 and 10 years ago, in 2005. That November, he was a guest lecturer at Celebrate Voting, an Iowa-wide initiative to observe the 40-year anniversary of the Voting Rights Act of 1965. Were you at either event?

These articles appeared in The Daily Iowan from the University of Iowa Special Collections & University Archives.

#tbt With the dedication of the Mary Louise Petersen Residence Hall on July 21st, here is a look back to the last residence hall dedication, Slater Hall, on October 27, 1972.

Fred W. ("Duke") Slater, UI football star from 1918 to 1921, earned his BA in 1922 and Law degree in 1928 at the University of Iowa. Slater later became a lawyer and judge. This hall was originally named Rienow II in 1968, and was renamed at the suggestion of UI President Willard L. Boyd.

Photo from F.W. Kent Collection, UI Archives.

#tbt Acclaimed poet and author Margaret Walker (1915-1998), a UI alumna, was born 100 years ago this past Tuesday. Her writings include the poem For My People, written in 1940, and the novel Jubilee, published in 1966. Both of these works are housed in the UI Archives. For My People was her master's thesis; she returned to Iowa City in the early 1960s to complete Jubilee as her doctoral dissertation.

status_message: #tbt Reunions can be a joy. These three women, all graduates of the SUI Class of 1882, met again for the first time in 50 years when this photograph was taken on June 3, 1932. They are, left to right, Abbie Ellis Brown of Vinton, Iowa; Julia Caranagh McElroy of Iowa City; and Grace Hebard of Laramie, Wyoming. Miss Hebard, a professor at the University of Wyoming, was the first woman to receive a Bachelor of Science degree at Iowa. Gift of Jeanne Longmuir, UI Archives.

status_message: #tbt Steve Smith (1944-2009), a UI student from Marion, leads a hunger strike in downtown Iowa City in support of Civil Rights workers in Selma, Alabama, on March 17, 1965. The strike, held in front of the downtown post office on Linn Street 50 years ago, lasted eight days and raised about $3,000 in donations. Photo by Mike Toner for The Daily Iowan. Papers of Stephen Lynn Smith (RG 02.0009.032), UI Archives.

status_message: Adah F. (Hyde) Johnson (1892-1988) and Letta (Cary) Bledsoe (1892-1931), both of Des Moines, were the first two African American women to graduate from the State University of Iowa. Both received Bachelor of Arts degrees from the College of Liberal Arts in 1912. Mrs. Johnson for many years served as executive director of the Blue Triangle Branch of the YWCA in Des Moines; Mrs. Bledsoe taught at Bishop College in Texas. Images from the Hawkeye annual, 1912, UI Archives.

#tbt What's so special about this photo taken inside the Main Library on July 16, 1954? Between the pillar and the woman in black you will see a portion of one of America's most iconic works of art: Jackson Pollock's Mural. The view is to the northwest, facing the former north lobby exhibit area. Recently restored by staff at the Getty Museum, Mural has been on tour and will be the subject of a UI documentary to be released soon. Image from F.W. Kent Collection, UI Archives.

#tbt Anyone remember the CRANDIC trolley, the passenger line that ran between Cedar Rapids and Iowa City during the first half of the 20th century? This is a wintertime view of a CRANDIC car passing over Templin Road (today, North Riverside Drive), taken sometime between 1911 and 1920. The bridge was replaced long ago but the site of the overpass remains at the same location today. Photo from F.W. Kent Collection, UI Archives.

#TBT Happy Homecoming Week, Hawkeyes! Our long, proud tradition began in 1912, over a century ago. Not long after it started, students in the College of Engineering started their own tradition ‚Äì the Iowa corn monument ‚Äì a work of art displayed in front of the Old Capitol during the week leading up to the game. The tradition stopped for a time during the 1960s and 1970s but has returned this week. You can see images of earlier monuments in the Iowa Digital Library at http://digital.lib.uiowa.edu/ictcs/ - search "corn monument." This gem is from 1934. Image from Kent Collection, UI Archives. #Homecoming102

#tbt Ready for some summertime blockbuster movies? From the angle of this 1930 photo it was anybody's guess what was playing at the Varsity Theater's afternoon matinee. Still, it was a safe bet that it featured an early talkie with, perhaps, Carole Lombard or Laurel and Hardy. The 500-seat Varsity, at 214 East Washington Street, opened in 1915 and closed in the 1990s. The site today is part of an addition to a nearby bank. Image courtesy F.W. Kent Collection, UI Archives.

Join UI business alumni at the Iowa 80 Trucking Museum, just north of the Iowa 80 Truck Stop off the Walcott exit, for a family-friendly Tippie College event. This Iowa gem is owned and operated by UI grads Delia Meier, BBA87 and Will Moon, BBA83.

#tbt When the Joffrey Ballet performed at Hancher Auditorium in February 1986, members of the ensemble signed a backstage guest book following the program. That book, chronicling events at the Hancher from 1983 to 1989, is now in the UI Archives. It features the autographs of a variety of luminaries, including Stan Getz, Rachel Lampert and Dancers, the Kronos Quartet, and the Dresden Chamber Orchestra. Image from Accession 2014-21, UI Archives.

status_message: #tbt Who remembers LP records? The UI Archives recently received this treat from an anonymous donor, a phonograph LP record featuring the Hawkeye Marching Band, the Men's Chorus, and the Scottish Highlanders, circa 1957. The Archives will have this record digitally reformatted later this year so that we can again enjoy such crowd-pleasers as The Iowa Fight Song, On Iowa, The Old Gold Hymn, and Scotland the Brave. The record was released by the State University of Iowa Alumni Association.

#tbt Alice Chase was secretary to two University of Iowa presidents during the late 1800s and early 1900s. She was also an avid photographer. During the summer of 1905, Calvin Hall (then known as Old Science Building) was moved across Jefferson Street from the Pentacrest to its present location, a job that took about three months. Her camera recorded an early stage of the process when Old Science was removed from its original foundation. Image from Alice B. Chase Collection of Photographs, UI Archives.

In light of recent sexual assaults in Iowa City and on campus, University of Iowa President Sally Mason has issued the following statement:
"Sexual assault is a terrible crime, one for which there is no excuse. The UI will take all the actions in our power to prevent rapes, to support victims and to prosecute offenders.  Even one sexual assault in our community is too many and we must confront this together as a community. I am committed to do everything in my power to end this terrible crime on our campus."

#tbt When the State University of Iowa opened for classes in 1855 it didn't even have any buildings to call its own. Instead, it rented rooms in the Mechanics' Academy, the site of UI's first classes. This photo is from 1897, shortly before it was demolished to make room for the new hospital, today known as Seashore Hall. Image from F.W. Kent Collection, UI Archives.

status_message: Alice Chase was secretary to two UI presidents (Schaeffer and MacLean) from 1897 to 1908. She was also an avid photographer. Her photo album in the UI Archives features some unique campus scenes, including the 1905 move of Old Science Hall (now Calvin Hall) across Jefferson Street from the Pentacrest. The building was moved on rollers several feet each day over three months‚Äîall while classes continued to meet inside!

Among the University of Iowa's sustainability targets is an effort to achieve 60 percent waste diversion by 2020. In an effort to approach this goal, the university transitioned to single-stream recycling, making it easier to recycle on campus.

Actual proof that the Quadrangle residence hall did, indeed, have four sides at one time. This aerial view was taken in 1920, less than five years after completion of the structure west of the Iowa River. A surplus of on-campus housing space prompted the university to demolish a portion of Quad in 1975, leaving only three sides. Photo courtesy of UI Archives.

Today we know it as Stuit Hall, recently renovated and named for Dewey Stuit, dean of the College of Liberal Arts from 1955 to 1977. status_message: Sixty years ago this summer, Danforth Chapel was being constructed just south of the IMU. The red brick structure, accented with white trim around the windows, door, and frame, has been a UI landmark since its dedication in January 1953. Funding was provided in part by William Danforth, co-founder of the Ralston-Purina Company, and by the Danforth Foundation, which helped construct similar chapels at two dozen colleges and universities across the U.S. A plaque on the building offers this challenge: "Aspire nobly. Adventure daringly. Serve humbly." Photo courtesy of UI Archives.

Long before Duane Banks Baseball Stadium, the Hawkeyes played their games on Iowa Field, a stretch of land along the east bank of the Iowa River, between Burlington Street and Iowa Avenue, hemmed in by railroad tracks to the east. This photo, taken in 1910, looks toward that direction. Old Capitol is visible in the background. Iowa Field was replaced by Iowa Stadium in 1928, which was renamed in honor of Nile Kinnick in 1972.
